I'd wager this is them wanting to push 1v1 as a monetizable format, not having the time/resources to code separate ban list setups for multiplayer, and not thinking through the ramifications of the message that may send. That isn't to say they don't also want to take control of multiplayer from the rules committee but I'd guess we get a separation between the two formats sooner rather than later once they realize they've caused more problems than they've fixed by thinking nobody would care outside mtgo

The whole thing just feels like a new CEO sent out a memo about expanding revenue streams. Edh has always been a pain for stores to cash in on outside pre-cons anyway and pushing 1v1 gives them a way to set up tournaments, etc. I guess the question winds up being so they think they can convert most edh players to the 1v1 format or do they think it's something to run in parallel to existing multiplayer. The former seems super risky, and wotc is pretty risk-averse in recent history.
Additionally it's not like there wasn't a history of mtgo not matching paper. Aren't cards like panglacial wurm simply not coded into online? At least once upon a time that was the case
There are a bunch of sets that haven't been pushed to mtgo, and they don't tend to put supplementary sets in unless it is all reprints
